2
00:00:05,270 --> 00:00:06,850
Did his hometown of Phoenix,

3
00:00:06,850 --> 00:00:10,240
Arizona help him cope with those stressful
heated conditions?

4
00:00:10,240 --> 00:00:10,960
Let's take a look.

5
00:00:12,570 --> 00:00:15,500
First, a friendly reminder of what
questions we left you with at

6
00:00:15,500 --> 00:00:17,530
the end of the Corey Gets Hot video.

7
00:00:18,860 --> 00:00:23,210
How did Corey's body cool down if the room
was warmer than his core temperature?

8
00:00:23,210 --> 00:00:27,440
Why does putting his hands in cold water
help lower his core temperature so much?

9
00:00:27,440 --> 00:00:30,560
And why did Corey's heart rate stay
elevated well after exercise?

10
00:00:32,570 --> 00:00:36,390
To my right, is a graph of Corey's core
temperature data as measured by

11
00:00:36,390 --> 00:00:39,060
the esophageal probe over the course of
the experiment.

12
00:00:41,010 --> 00:00:45,600
There was a rapid rise in core temperature
during the set workload exercise.

13
00:00:45,600 --> 00:00:50,490
Remember that he was in a double-layered
charcoal suit that was semi-impermeable.

14
00:00:50,490 --> 00:00:54,070
The room was 104 degrees Fahrenheit, or 40
degrees centigrade.

15
00:00:54,070 --> 00:00:58,201
Within 20 minutes, his temperature went up
two degrees,

16
00:00:58,201 --> 00:01:01,926
from 37.25 to 39.25 degrees centigrade.

17
00:01:04,430 --> 00:01:08,040
Then he got off the treadmill and there
was an initial fall in temperature as

18
00:01:08,040 --> 00:01:12,050
we put on his additional coverage; gloves
on his hands, baggies on his feet, and

19
00:01:12,050 --> 00:01:13,468
a ski mask.

20
00:01:13,468 --> 00:01:16,260
In that scenario, we were able to clamp
his core temperature,

21
00:01:16,260 --> 00:01:19,980
because there was essentially no way for
him to dissipate his heat.

22
00:01:19,980 --> 00:01:21,480
You can see by the yellow line,

23
00:01:21,480 --> 00:01:24,200
that his temperature remained stable
during that time.

24
00:01:25,380 --> 00:01:28,430
We then uncovered his head, his hands and
feet.

25
00:01:28,430 --> 00:01:31,010
His core temperature began to fall again.

26
00:01:31,010 --> 00:01:34,050
Check out the light blue section of the
line on that graph.

27
00:01:34,050 --> 00:01:35,630
Amazing.

28
00:01:35,630 --> 00:01:39,020
So it seems intuitive that he would not be
able to lose heat when he

29
00:01:39,020 --> 00:01:40,500
was completely covered up.

30
00:01:40,500 --> 00:01:43,500
But what about the first Corey question.

31
00:01:43,500 --> 00:01:46,130
How did he lose heat when he was
unclamped, and

32
00:01:46,130 --> 00:01:47,589
the room was warmer than he was?

33
00:01:48,860 --> 00:01:52,430
Well there's really only one option,
evaporation.

34
00:01:52,430 --> 00:01:55,670
He was cooling the exposed skin areas
through evaporation.

35
00:01:56,750 --> 00:02:00,170
Converting liquid to gas requires the
input of energy.

36
00:02:00,170 --> 00:02:03,450
That energy is drawn from the heat in the
surface of the skin that's

37
00:02:03,450 --> 00:02:04,350
cooling the skin.

38
00:02:06,340 --> 00:02:08,650
And then he put his hands down in the cold
water, and

39
00:02:08,650 --> 00:02:12,710
his temperature began to fall even more
rapidly, as indicated by the purple line.

40
00:02:13,830 --> 00:02:15,150
And the second question.

41
00:02:15,150 --> 00:02:19,350
Why did his temperature fall more rapidly
when he put his hands in the cool water?

42
00:02:19,350 --> 00:02:23,330
By doing that, we provided him with an
external cold sink.

43
00:02:23,330 --> 00:02:26,040
His body was sending hot blood down to his
hands,

44
00:02:26,040 --> 00:02:29,530
where it came in contact with the cool
water, dumped some of the heat, and

45
00:02:29,530 --> 00:02:31,410
brought the cooler blood back to the core.

46
00:02:32,410 --> 00:02:36,460
If the water had been too cold, then it
would have caused localized

47
00:02:36,460 --> 00:02:39,930
vasoconstriction, and the heat exchange
would not have been optimal.

48
00:02:39,930 --> 00:02:42,060
However, when the temperature's in the
right range,

49
00:02:42,060 --> 00:02:43,830
it can serve as an effective heat sink.

50
00:02:45,300 --> 00:02:48,800
It must have felt like such a relief for
poor Corey in that crazy outfit.

51
00:02:48,800 --> 00:02:50,380
What a good sport he is, eh?

52
00:02:50,380 --> 00:02:53,190
[LAUGH]

53
00:02:53,190 --> 00:02:57,280
In this graph, Corey's heart rate data in
